land's colonial regime required stringent monetary regulation. As Barth shows, money was also a flash point for resistance; many colonists acutely resented their subordinate economic station, desiring for their local economies a robust, secure, and uniform money supply. This placed them immediately at odds with the mercantilist laws of the empire and precipitated an imperial crisis in the 1670s, a full century before the Declaration of Independence.The Currency of Empire examines what were a series of explosive political conflicts in the seventeenth century and demonstrates how the struggle over monetary policy prefigured the Patriot reaction to the Stamp Act and so-called Intolerable Acts on the eve of American Independence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aFiscal policyzUnited StatesxHistoryy17th century. 0aMercantile systemzUnited StatesxHistoryy17th century. 0aMoneyxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy17th century. 4aBritish History. 4aEconomic History. 4aU.S. History. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh  acoin in colonial America, political history of colonial America, mercantilism in Colonial America.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073908440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501755781zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501755781.jpg  a978-3-11-073908-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA